<dl id="n08066n"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n08" href="#n08066n">N08 (VI.B.6)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n08all.htm#n08066n"> 66(n)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ~ battle of eye &amp; egg <small>Not cancelled</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n08066n"><li>FW 199.06 </li><li><a href="../../flex/h/lexh.htm#n08066n">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/h/l39h.htm#n08066n">1939</a>,16 </li><li><ms href="#n08066n">MS BL 47474-108</ms> </li><li>JJA 48:041 <a name="hd2" href="../../FF/fdra/hda.htm#hd2">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/h/hd2.htm#n08066n">Draft: I.8&sect;1.2</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">Caxton &hellip; gives us a graphic description of the struggle between the native <i>ey</i> and the Scandinavian <i>egg</i>: And certaynly our langage now used varyeth ferre from that whiche was used and spoken whan I was borne. For we englysshe men ben borne under the domynacyon of the mone, whiche is never stedfaste &hellip;. And that comyn englysshe that is spoken in one shyre varyeth from a nother. In so moche that in my dayes happened that certayn marchauntes were in a shippe in tamyse, for to have sayled over the see into zelande. &hellip; And <b>one of theym named sheffelde</b> &hellip;, cam in-to an hows and axed for mete; and specyally he axyd after eggys. &hellip; Loo, what sholde a man in thyse dayes now wryte, egges or eyren. Certaynly it is harde to playse every man, by cause of dyversite &amp; chaunge of langage. <small> Otto Jespersen, <a name="OJGS" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#OJGS"><cite title="source">The Growth and Structure of the English Language</cite></a>, 4th ed. (Jul 1923) 67</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: The &ldquo;eyes&rdquo; from the previous draft suddenly have been changed into &ldquo;eygs&rdquo;</mm> </dd></dl>
